format_description: Traditional bracket where one loss eliminates team/player
Bracket with winners and losers brackets - teams get second chance after first loss
Every team/player competes against every other participant - comprehensive competition format
Groups compete in round robin pools, then top teams advance to single elimination bracket
Teams paired based on similar records. No elimination, predetermined number of rounds.
Pool play followed by double elimination bracket for advanced teams.
Single or double elimination with teams ranked and positioned based on skill/ranking.
Lower-seeded teams must "climb the ladder" by defeating higher seeds sequentially.
One champion faces all challengers sequentially. Champion retains position until defeated.
Participants eliminated based on cumulative performance across multiple rounds.
Participants eliminated after losing three matches. Extended competition format.
Sequential challenges where participants must complete entire course without elimination.
Round robin group stage followed by single elimination bracket with top performers.
Multiple groups compete internally, winners advance to knockout elimination rounds
Complete round robin followed by single championship game between top two teams.
Qualification rounds determine participants for final competition rounds.
Multiple pools with internal play, top teams from each pool advance to playoff bracket.
Ranked ladder system where participants challenge higher-ranked opponents to move up.
Matches decided by first to win 2 games. Used for extended competition.
Matches decided by first to win 3 games. Professional tournament standard.
Matches decided by first to win 4 games. Championship series format.
Winners determined by best performance within specified time limit
Multiple timed segments with cumulative scoring or elimination.
Continuous ranking system based on ongoing performance metrics
Multiple skill-based challenges with combined scoring to determine winner.
Combined events with points awarded across different competitive areas.
Performance evaluated by panel of judges using standardized criteria.
Points accumulated across multiple rounds or events to determine final standing.
User-defined tournament structure with flexible rules and advancement criteria
Multi-event competition with track events, field events, or combined meet format"
